05947nam a22008415i 9780292733244DE-B159720211129102213.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||211129t20212011txu    fo  d z      eng d  a97802927332447 a10.7560/7233062doi  a(DE-B1597)588120  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  atxucUS-TX 4aQC981.8.G56bI47 2011eb 7aNAT0000002bisacsh04a363.738 7420976422204aThe Impact of Global Warming on Texas :bSecond edition /ced. by Jurgen Schmandt, Judith Clarkson, Gerald R. North. 1aAustin : bUniversity of Texas Press, c[2021] 4c©2011  a1 online resource (328 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tForeword -- tContributors -- tIntroduction -- tContributors -- tChapter 1. Climate Science and Climate Change -- tChapter 2. The Changing Climate of Texas -- tChapter 3. Water Resources and Water Supply -- tChapter 4. Coastal Impacts -- tChapter 5. Biodiversity -- tChapter 6. Agriculture -- tChapter 7. Urban Areas -- tChapter 8. Greenhouse Gas Emissions -- tChapter 9. Economy -- tChapter 10. Policy -- tContributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aWhen The Impact of Global Warming on Texas was first published in 1995, it discussed climate change as a likely future phenomenon, predicted by scientific studies. This entirely rewritten second edition presents evidence that early climate change impacts can now be observed and identifies the threats climate change will pose to Texas through the year 2050. It also offers the hopeful message that corrective action, if taken now, can avert unmanageable consequences. The book begins with a discussion of climate science and modeling and the information that can be derived from these sources for Texas. The authors follow this with an analysis of actual climate trends in the various Texas climate regions, including a predicted rise in temperatures of 5.4 degrees F (plus or minus 1.8 F) by the end of the century. This could lead to less rainfall and higher evaporation, especially in regions that are already dry. Other important effects include possible changes in El Niño (climate variability) patterns and hurricane behaviors. Taking into account projected population growth, subsequent chapters explore likely trends with respect to water availability, coastal impacts, and biodiversity. The authors then look at the issues from a policy perspective, focusing on Texas's importance to the national economy as an energy producer, particularly of oil and gas. They recommend that Texas develop its own climate change policy to serve the goals of reducing greenhouse gas emissions, increasing energy independence, ensuring regional security, and improving management of water, air, land, and wildlife.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 0aClimatic changesxEnvironmental aspectsxTexas. 0aClimatic changeszTexas. 0aGlobal warmingxTexas. 0aGlobal warmingzTexas. 7aNATURE / General.2bisacsh1 aBrenner, Jorge, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aClarkson, Judith, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aClarkson, Judith, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aDawson, Bill, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGammon, John, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGibeaut, James, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGordon, Wendy, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHazleton, Jared, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHitchcock, David, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLane, Neal, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.go